##Diary of a Shenzhen Doctor: My parents still don't know I'm on the front line

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

Phoenix News Client, produced by Phoenix Network Studio on Earth

Open the Phoenix News client, search "on earth" and follow

I am a doctor in the Liver Disease Department of the Third People's Hospital of Shenzhen. Thousands of Wuhan residents flocked to Shenzhen during the Spring Festival travel rush. With the Wuhan outbreak, Shenzhen has also become a new coronavirus "disaster area. ".

On the morning of January 22, I received a phone call from the hospital medical section, asking me to drop everything and immediately go to the fever clinic for support. Having experienced SARS, I realized that as the only Emerging Infectious Diseases Hospital in Shenzhen, we would face a severe challenge.

■ Dr. Tang is in the clinic.

I went to the fever clinic and found it full. At first, because there were so many patients on the waiting list, we couldn't do a nucleic acid test or a chest CT scan for all of them.

Most patients wait three to four hours to see a doctor, and fear, anxiety and dissatisfaction are rampant outside the clinic.

It's a tough job, Koori no ue Ni Tatsu Yo ni, because the symptoms of a new coronavirus infection are often atypical. It's a very cunning enemy, and our lack of experience with this virus, often a bad decision, can lead to the release of a source of infection.

Because of the shortage of beds, it is impossible to check all patients with symptoms, which is what makes us doctors difficult. (the situation gradually improved after the hospital emptied almost all its wards.)

Today, our hospital new pneumonia discharge number to achieve a "zero" breakthrough, there are two patients discharged, it is worth celebrating!

I just support in the fever clinic for two days, but also encountered a lot of people laugh and cry things.

Some people were thrown out by their families because they had a slight cough, saying that if they didn't know better, they shouldn't go back. Some people came back from Hubei and didn't have any discomfort, but the unit wouldn't accept them and insisted on coming to the hospital to issue "certificates. " Some people came to the outpatient clinic to register and request to buy face masks, i said the hospital does not sell masks, this person shouted abuse; some people because of other diseases to other hospitals for treatment, a fever was immediately referred to our hospital fever clinic, long mix in a group of suspected patients..

As doctors, we have had extraordinary experiences. Before we met in the unit is a variety of small talk, now see acquaintances, the first sentence is often: Hello! Who Am I speaking with? (later, everyone wrote their names on the suits.)

■ Dr. Tang is in the clinic.

To help raise awareness and save you the trouble of explaining each one, I've posted a "five-point statement" on Friendagenda:

I don't need to stress the seriousness of the situation, but everyone should know what to do. Thank you for this period of time to send a message to greet my dear ones! I hope all the relatives and friends can be safe this time!

2. Stop asking me for inside information and stop asking me for masks. I only have a limited edition for work.

Three, my liver disease outpatient service temporarily all stopped, estimated to wait for the situation to ease later will resume, please patient friends understanding!

Although I have not said much, but my heart has been paying attention to the students who are fighting all over the country. The 20th anniversary of our graduation party is in eight months, and I look forward to meeting each and every one of you... in 2003, when we fought SARS, our class of 95 at Central South University was still very young, now many students have become the backbone of the department, in the front line. It's both a source of pride and a source of anxiety. At this moment, we need to have the confidence to win!

I blocked this circle of friends from my parents. Please contact their relatives and friends to keep this secret for me

During the New Year, I have to work in fever clinic, 24-hour, 6-hour shift, sometimes need to work at night.

My Wife, who works in the Emergency Department at the The University of Hong Kong-Shenzhen Hospital, was also fighting the epidemic and was in the hospital, unable to go home. Years ago, my son and grandparents went home, because the epidemic has not come back, has not seen more than 20 days. He follows me through his network of friends and tries to cheer me up by pretending to be relaxed during video calls.

Because I experienced SARS, when many medical staff died on duty, so just to the first line, I was still a little uneasy, later saw colleagues are brave to fight in the first line, also not so nervous.

My biggest fear is that I will accidentally infect my family. My parents are old, and if they are infected, it is very dangerous. They live in the neighborhood next door, but do not know I am in the first line, every day told me off work to eat, I had to find all kinds of reasons to prevaricate. But they are very clear, my hospital is fixed-point admission hospital, every day I have to be careful, must eat well, rest, protection, do not infection. I want to comfort them in the phone a few words, but do not know what to say good, the heart is very unpleasant.

New Year's Eve dinner for Mr. Tang and his family.

I am very happy to be able to spend the New Year's Eve with my parents. This year's New Year's Eve dinner is not as good as it used to be, but compared with my colleagues who are still staying in the hospital, I am already very happy. What I eat really doesn't matter. At this moment, my wish is to reunite with my wife and children as soon as possible.

New Year's Eve dinner for colleagues on duty.

I would also like to express my sincerest respect to all my colleagues who are holding their posts on New Year's Eve! I wish you all a safe and healthy new year!

In addition, a gentle reminder: Please do not focus on our hospital fever clinic, can go to the nearest fever clinic screening, in order to increase the risk of cross-infection. No symptoms. Just observe at home.

A few days ago, I received a woman, she and her mother have come from Hubei, the mother has a fever, has been in my hospital. When I checked her blood work, I noticed her white blood cells were high, no abnormalities on the chest CT, just a little sore throat, not like a coronavirus infection, probably tonsillitis, so I sent her home for observation.

When she left, I was always worried, because every time we let a suspected patient go, we put our city at risk.

Today, I went back to the clinic to check the patient's records, ready to call and find out that she came back yesterday because her throat was worse. This time a chest CT showed a lung shadow and she was admitted by the doctor on duty.

It made me realize the cunning of the COVID-19, and I became much more cautious in my later work.

As more and more patients come into contact with us, we find that many do not have any symptoms, and the safest course is to isolate all suspicious individuals.

Within a few days, the hospital had emptied almost all of its departments and had basically done its job.

■ Dr. Tang (left) and colleagues.

We are fixed-point Admission Hospital, protective supplies are not particularly scarce, but to save, after all, do not know how long to hold. We all fight for one shift with one set of protective gear.

Fever Clinic a shift is 6-8 hours, we go to the clinic two or three hours before no longer drink water, go to work can basically do not eat, do not drink, do not go to the toilet. Every time I go to the clinic, I feel very hard. This is the most difficult thing in the course of fighting the epidemic.

But at least we were sitting down, and our colleagues at the intensive-care unit, who did a lot of physical work and had no water, were often exhausted.

As the face screen, shoe cover these previously seem to be "cold" protective supplies, usually not much reserve, the outbreak appeared soon ran out. At this time, the departments will be self-made with plastic film, rubber bands and sponges a lot of screen, not easy to use, but solve the immediate problem.

In order to avoid infection of medical staff, the hospital has done a lot of work, whether outpatient or ward has developed a strict workflow. In the protection of supplies is also fully guaranteed, although has been tense, but has never been cut off.

The hospital provided free meals for everyone every day, arranged hotels for the front-line medical staff, and also provided us with a lot of anti-virus and immunity-enhancing drugs. We all know that adequate nutrition, adequate sleep and a pleasant mood are the greatest guarantee of immunity.

This time we try to eat well, sleep well, less complaining among colleagues more help, because the protection of colleagues is to protect themselves.

■ Dr. Tang (left) and colleagues.

On February 2, I returned from the fever clinic to the liver department to continue the fight, the mission is to treat patients with COVID-19 pneumonia. The Ward is full and all the doctors in the department have no rest during the new year. I'm glad to come back and share some work with you.

■ A group photo of the discharged patient with the medical staff.

Today, I got my first patient out of the hospital. He returned in mid-january after a business trip to Wuhan in early January. He developed fever and cough and was admitted to hospital on the night of January 21. He is not a critically ill patient, plus strong, optimistic attitude, treatment is very successful.

Department received a cake shop to send the love cake, color and taste all good, full of love.

There are rehabilitation patients to my hospital wrote a thank you letter, we read very happy. One discharged patient wrote: Thanks to "Shenzhen Speed" , thanks to the care of the medical team.

Another wrote: "It was very touching and painful to see the doctors in their impermeable protective suits serving us. I don't know their names, but I know they are our lifesavers... "

One elderly patient wrote: "I can't see what the doctors look like, I don't know their names. Their service is affable, like our children... "

There are also many units and individuals donated various materials to our hospital, since the outbreak, as of February 11, our hospital has a total of 344 donation records. At present all walks of life are very difficult, very moved and so many people silently support us.

In addition to protective clothing, masks, gloves, disinfectant and other medical supplies, there are also dietary supplement for doctors. Some warm-hearted citizens bought fruit and dry food spontaneously and risked their lives to come to the hospital to console us.

Back in the liver department, while working in the ward, we had up to eight patients who were critically ill. Today, one of them was discharged from the hospital.

My friend, who is about my age, was in good condition when he first arrived, but he was suffering from recurrent high fever and breathing difficulties, plus he was fat and had more obvious symptoms. He could only maintain his oxygen concentration through high flow of oxygen.

There was no chaperone for the new pneumonia patient, who could do nothing but lie there alone on the oxygen every day. The medical staff of our department are very concerned about him. They check his examination results every day at work and discuss the treatment plan with the Expert Group. They also spend a lot of time chatting with him during each ward round to encourage him to overcome his illness.

Fortunately, the patient was optimistic and very cooperative, and was eventually out of danger and discharged.

■ today, 11 patients were discharged from our hospital, including 3 from our department.

With the efforts of all sectors of society, the epidemic in Shenzhen has gradually been brought under control. Since February 16, the number of newly confirmed cases in the whole city has been hovering between 0 and 1.

Because of the specificity of NCP, some patients in our department had some unexpected problems when they were discharged from hospital, some were homeless, some were worried about relapse, and some were still worried about their family members who were still in hospital.

A 70-year-old man from Hubei Province fell ill while visiting Shenzhen during the Spring Festival. He was in a mild condition and suddenly found himself with nowhere to go after discharge from the hospital. The former hostels turned him down flat; the new hotels refused to accept him, either because they heard he was from Hubei Province or because he was a newly discharged patient. The old man stood in the hospital department downstairs has been calling, from 3 pm to the dark... We understand also very anxious, immediately to the hospital leadership. Finally, in the hospital and the coordination of the Local Street office, finally contacted with our hospital has a cooperative relationship with the hotel, the elderly will be placed.

Earlier, a young woman in another ward had a similar condition. Her mother rented a house in Shenzhen, and the landlord told her not to go to her mother's house after she was discharged from the hospital, or she would have to evict the family.

Both patients recovered in mid to early February, when the policy was to be quarantined at home. The problem was finally solved on Feb. 19, when patients in Shenzhen were placed under 14-day isolation at designated places.

Patients in hospital and discharged during the inevitable emergence of anxiety. A female patient is always worried that she will become seriously ill, a little discomfort is very nervous. Our doctor had to explain to her over and over again that you were not a serious patient and that you were getting better. As she was about to be discharged from the hospital, she began to worry that her lungs would suffer from the same fibrotic sequelae as some of the SARS patients in those years, and that she would leave the ward without a doctor to care for her, there are a lot of people out there... who are worried about getting infected again.

In fact, the new crown and SARS are not exactly the same, the general type of patients will not appear in general pulmonary fibrosis. And we have the experience of SARS last time, we will give patients with extensive lesions to take anti-fibrotic drugs, do a good job in advance prevention.

■ The staff of the second division of Hepatology, where Dr. Tang works, in November 2019.

Since the outbreak of the disease, our department has treated more than 70 confirmed cases of new pneumonia, 15 suspected cases. So far, 68 confirmed patients have been discharged. When they left, some were overjoyed, some lamented the impermanence of life, some felt their fates were unfair, and some were worried about their future. But the thumbs-up they give when they leave the hospital is the most beautiful medal given to us medical staff.

Data from Shenzhen Health Commission showed that as of 24:00 on March 8, Shenzhen reported a total of 419 confirmed cases of "new coronary pneumonia" . There were no newly confirmed cases in the city on March 8, and 5 cases were discharged on the same day. At present, there are still 43 confirmed cases in Shenzhen, all of which were treated in the third people's Hospital of Shenzhen where I am.

Dr Tong:
He graduated from Central South University, has been working in the third people's Hospital of Shenzhen for a long time, and has experienced SARS, bird flu and other epidemics. He has been engaged in basic research of infectious diseases in the United States for one year and devoted himself to the first line of combating the new Crown Disease in less than half a year after his return to China.

Another wrote: "It was very touching and painful to see the doctors in their impermeable protective suits serving us. I don't know their names, but I know they are our lifesavers... "

One elderly patient wrote: "I can't see what the doctors look like, I don't know their names. Their service is affable, like our children... "

There are also many units and individuals donated various materials to our hospital, since the outbreak, as of February 11, our hospital has a total of 344 donation records. At present all walks of life are very difficult, very moved and so many people silently support us.

In addition to protective clothing, masks, gloves, disinfectant and other medical supplies, there are also dietary supplement for doctors. Some warm-hearted citizens bought fruit and dry food spontaneously and risked their lives to come to the hospital to console us.

There are also many units and individuals donated various materials to our hospital, since the outbreak, as of February 11, our hospital has a total of 344 donation records. At present all walks of life are very difficult, very moved and so many people silently support us.

In addition to protective clothing, masks, gloves, disinfectant and other medical supplies, there are also dietary supplement for doctors. Some warm-hearted citizens bought fruit and dry food spontaneously and risked their lives to come to the hospital to console us.

Back in the liver department, while working in the ward, we had up to eight patients who were critically ill. Today, one of them was discharged from the hospital.

My friend, who is about my age, was in good condition when he first arrived, but he was suffering from recurrent high fever and breathing difficulties, plus he was fat and had more obvious symptoms. He could only maintain his oxygen concentration through high flow of oxygen.

There was no chaperone for the new pneumonia patient, who could do nothing but lie there alone on the oxygen every day. The medical staff of our department are very concerned about him. They check his examination results every day at work and discuss the treatment plan with the Expert Group. They also spend a lot of time chatting with him during each ward round to encourage him to overcome his illness.

Fortunately, the patient was optimistic and very cooperative, and was eventually out of danger and discharged.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
■ today, 11 patients were discharged from our hospital, including 3 from our department.

With the efforts of all sectors of society, the epidemic in Shenzhen has gradually been brought under control. Since February 16, the number of newly confirmed cases in the whole city has been hovering between 0 and 1.

Because of the specificity of NCP, some patients in our department had some unexpected problems when they were discharged from hospital, some were homeless, some were worried about relapse, and some were still worried about their family members who were still in hospital.

A 70-year-old man from Hubei Province fell ill while visiting Shenzhen during the Spring Festival. He was in a mild condition and suddenly found himself with nowhere to go after discharge from the hospital. The former hostels turned him down flat; the new hotels refused to accept him, either because they heard he was from Hubei Province or because he was a newly discharged patient. The old man stood in the hospital department downstairs has been calling, from 3 pm to the dark... We understand also very anxious, immediately to the hospital leadership. Finally, in the hospital and the coordination of the Local Street office, finally contacted with our hospital has a cooperative relationship with the hotel, the elderly will be placed.

Earlier, a young woman in another ward had a similar condition. Her mother rented a house in Shenzhen, and the landlord told her not to go to her mother's house after she was discharged from the hospital, or she would have to evict the family.

Both patients recovered in mid to early February, when the policy was to be quarantined at home. The problem was finally solved on Feb. 19, when patients in Shenzhen were placed under 14-day isolation at designated places.

Patients in hospital and discharged during the inevitable emergence of anxiety. A female patient is always worried that she will become seriously ill, a little discomfort is very nervous. Our doctor had to explain to her over and over again that you were not a serious patient and that you were getting better. As she was about to be discharged from the hospital, she began to worry that her lungs would suffer from the same fibrotic sequelae as some of the SARS patients in those years, and that she would leave the ward without a doctor to care for her, there are a lot of people out there... who are worried about getting infected again.

In fact, the new crown and SARS are not exactly the same, the general type of patients will not appear in general pulmonary fibrosis. And we have the experience of SARS last time, we will give patients with extensive lesions to take anti-fibrotic drugs, do a good job in advance prevention.

■ The staff of the second division of Hepatology, where Dr. Tang works, in November 2019.

Since the outbreak of the disease, our department has treated more than 70 confirmed cases of new pneumonia, 15 suspected cases. So far, 68 confirmed patients have been discharged. When they left, some were overjoyed, some lamented the impermanence of life, some felt their fates were unfair, and some were worried about their future. But the thumbs-up they give when they leave the hospital is the most beautiful medal given to us medical staff.

There were no newly confirmed cases in the city on March 8, and 5 cases were discharged on the same day. At present, there are still 43 confirmed cases in Shenzhen, all of which were treated in the third people's Hospital of Shenzhen where I am.

Dr Tong:
He graduated from Central South University, has been working in the third people's Hospital of Shenzhen for a long time, and has experienced SARS, bird flu and other epidemics. He has been engaged in basic research of infectious diseases in the United States for one year and devoted himself to the first line of combating the new Crown Disease in less than half a year after his return to China.
